k Holmes stories, Misrecognitions tracks how the Victorian novel translates the financialized abstractions of capital into dramas of buried secrets and disguised relations. Drawing on Karl Marx's account of commodity fetishism and reification, Parker contends that, by configuring capital as an enigma to be unveiled, Victorian recognition scenes dramatize the inversions of agency and temporality that are repressed in capitalist production. In plotting capital as an agent of opacity and misdirection, Victorian novels and their characteristic dialectic of illusion and illumination reveal the plot hole in capitalism itself.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aCapitalism in literature. 0aEnglish literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aRecognition in literature. 4aECONOMIC HISTORY. 4aWEST EUROPEAN HISTORY. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Modern / 19th Century .2bisacsh  acommodity fetishism, Marxism, recognition scenes, Charles Dickens, Anthony Trollope, Henry James, Arthur Conan Doyle.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311075184040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781501774096?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501774096423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501774096/original  a978-3-11-075184-0  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles